@node Install "MindGuard: Installing"

Simply copy the MindGuard drawer, along with all its contents,
wherever you want it.

The MindGuard drawer must contain the carrier drawer with some
carrier modules if you want MindGuard to run.  MindGuard looks
in the drawer it is in to find the carriers and will not run
if it doesn't find them.  If you wish, you can change the place
MindGuard looks by editing the CARDIR @{" tooltype " link Tool}.

If you are going to run MindGuard from a shell, you must either
be in MindGuard's drawer, or use the CARDIR @{" argument " link Tool} to specify
where the carrier drawer is.

Likewise, if you use Toolmanager or any similar program, you
must set the current directory to where the carrier drawer is.

@endnode

@node Use "MindGuard: Usage"

GETTING STARTED:

  Make sure MindGuard is properly @{" installed " link Install}.

  Double click on the MindGuard icon or type 'MindGuard'
  from the CLI.

  See the following sections for more specific information:

    @{" Window & Menus  " link Usage}
    @{" Tooltypes & CLI " link Tool}
    @{" Commodity       " link Cmdty}

    @{" Scanning        " link Scan}
    @{" Jamming         " link Jam}
    @{" DePsych         " link Depsych}
    @{" PsIdent         " link Psident}
    @{" Diagnostic      " link Diag}
    @{" Saving Prefs    " link Save}
    @{" FAILURE         " link Fail}

WHEN TO USE:

  In a word: ALWAYS. In fact, if you haven't run MindGuard yet, do
  so IMMEDIATELY!  Every second that you don't have it running, you
  are exposing yourself to potential MIND PROGRAMMING.

MINI FAQ ON USAGE:

  Q: How do I make MindGuard run in the background and display any
     messages it may decipher?
  A: Turn Auto Decipher on and Silent off then hide the window.

  Q: How do I make MindGuard run in the background without it
     upseting my well-being by displaying disturbing messages?
  A: Turn Silent on.

  Q: I want to see what sort of messages I am receiving but I don't
     want to be constantly bothered by MindGuard; what do I do?
  A: Use the Scan button to sate your curiosity.

  Q: If I leave the algorithm/scan method/scanner depth options at
     their default settings will I encounter any problems?
  A: No.  MindGuard is a very robust and adaptive system and will
     automatically try alternative settings should it judge the
     need.

  Q: How can I review the messages that MindGuard has deciphered?
  A: Turn Log on, wait for deciphered messages to accumulate, then
     open the log file with a text browser to view.

  Q: When I hit the Close Window gadget, MindGuard won't quit!
  A: Use the Quit button, the Quit menu item, or the Remove button
     in Exchange to quit MindGuard

  Q: I want to find out my friend/enemy's biorhythm/eponymolog but
     I don't want to compromise my security by having someone
     else's personal info in PsiDent, what should I do?
  A: Turn off the biorhythm/eponymolog feature(s), enter in the
     foreign data, get the results, then turn the feature(s) back
     on.

  A: I have a Wintel/Mac/*NIX/BeOS/etc. system that I mainly use,
     What should I do?
  Q: Set up your Amiga next to your other computer and run
     MindGuard.

  Q: MindGuard's hotkey won't work.  What's up with that?
  A: There may be a conflict between MindGuard and some other
     program.  Quit MindGuard and use the tooltypes or cli
     arguments to set another hotkey.

  Q: MindGuard uses the hotkey that my other program uses!  I don't
     like this!!
  A: Change MindGuard's hotkey or turn the hotkey recognition off
     by Inactivating MindGuard with Exchange.

  Q: How do I find out what the current hotkey is?
  A: Press the '?' button.

TIPS:

  · Don't watch @{" TV " link Tom} while out of range of your computer, it acts as
    an amplifier for most psychotronic carriers.
  · Consider an @{" AFDB " link AFDB} for security in case of power-outage.

@endnode

@node Tool "MindGuard: Tooltypes and CLI Arguments"

Some of MindGuard's options can only be selected at startup using
tooltypes and CLI arguments.  For more information on how to use
these, consult your Amiga manuals.

TOOLTYPES:

  PREFS     = <path to prefs file>
  LOGFILE   = <path to save log>
  CARDIR    = <path to carrier drawer>

  CX_POPUP  = <YES|NO> - controls if window is opened on startup.
  CX_POPKEY = <hotkey for window popup>

CLI ARGUMENTS:

  Template: PREFS/K,LOGFILE/K,CARDIR/K,CX_NOPOPUP/S,CX_POPKEY/K

  Most of these options work the same as the tooltypes.

  Example:

    MindGuard LOGFILE T:mg.log PREFS DH0:MindGuard/Jimmy.config

  CX_NOPOPUP is a switch that will keep MindGuard from opening
  its window on startup.

  When using CX_POPKEY you need to put double quotes around the
  hot-key string if it is more than one word long:

    MindGuard CX_POPKEY "ralt rshift m"

VIEWING SETTINGS FROM INSIDE MINDGUARD:

  The '?' button in the main window will display in the diagnostic
  box the current settings for the various tooltype/argument
  options.  The legend for the display is:

    C = Carrier drawer
    P = Prefs file
    L = Log file
    H = Hotkey

@endnode

